#Part 1.1 b - Print Shape and columns of all the 3 DataFrames
import pandas as pd

# Assuming you've successfully loaded your DataFrames as df_normal, df_type_h, and df_type_s

# Function to print shape and columns of a DataFrame
def print_info(df, name):
    print(f"Shape of {name}: {df.shape}")  # Print the shape of the DataFrame
    print(f"Columns of {name}: {list(df.columns)}\n")  # Print the columns of the DataFrame

# Print shape and columns of each DataFrame
print_info(df_normal, 'Normal')
print_info(df_type_h, 'Type_H')
print_info(df_type_s, 'Type_S')

#Part 1.1 c - Compare Column names of all the 3 DataFrames and clearly write observations
import pandas as pd

# Placeholder for actual DataFrames, replace with the actual DataFrames loaded from your CSV files
df_normal = pd.DataFrame(columns=['A', 'B', 'C'])
df_type_h = pd.DataFrame(columns=['B', 'C', 'D'])
df_type_s = pd.DataFrame(columns=['C', 'D', 'E'])

# Function to compare columns of three DataFrames and print observations
def compare_columns(df1, df2, df3, names):
    columns1 = set(df1.columns)
    columns2 = set(df2.columns)
    columns3 = set(df3.columns)

    # Identifying common and unique columns
    common_columns = columns1.intersection(columns2).intersection(columns3)
    unique_to_df1 = columns1 - columns2 - columns3
    unique_to_df2 = columns2 - columns1 - columns3
    unique_to_df3 = columns3 - columns1 - columns2

    # Printing observations
    print(f"Common columns in all three DataFrames ({names[0]}, {names[1]}, and {names[2]}): {common_columns}")
    print(f"Columns unique to {names[0]}: {unique_to_df1}")
    print(f"Columns unique to {names[1]}: {unique_to_df2}")
    print(f"Columns unique to {names[2]}: {unique_to_df3}\n")

# Compare and print observations
compare_columns(df_normal, df_type_h, df_type_s, ['Normal', 'Type_H', 'Type_S'])

Common columns in all three DataFrames (Normal, Type_H, and Type_S): {'C'}
Columns unique to Normal: {'A'}
Columns unique to Type_H: set()
Columns unique to Type_S: {'E'}

To compare the column names of the three DataFrames and provide observations, you can use the following Python code. This code will identify unique and common columns across the DataFrames and print out observations regarding their similarities and differences.

This script will output:

The common columns that exist in all three DataFrames. The columns that are unique to each DataFrame. This script will help you understand the similarities and differences in the structure of your DataFrames, which is crucial for tasks like merging, joining, and analyzing data across multiple sources

#Part 1.2 a - Unify all the variations in Class feature for all the 3 DataFrames
import pandas as pd

# Placeholder for actual DataFrames, replace these with the actual DataFrames loaded from your CSV files
df_normal = pd.DataFrame({'Class': ['A', 'b', 'a', 'C']})
df_type_h = pd.DataFrame({'Class': ['B', 'b', 'D', 'e']})
df_type_s = pd.DataFrame({'Class': ['a', 'C', 'c', 'd']})

# Define a standard naming convention for the 'Class' feature (e.g., all upper case)
standard_classes = {
    'A': 'A',
    'a': 'A',
    'B': 'B',
    'b': 'B',
    'C': 'C',
    'c': 'C',
    'D': 'D',
    'd': 'D',
    'E': 'E',
    'e': 'E'
    # Add more mappings as necessary for your data
}

# Function to unify 'Class' variations in a DataFrame
def unify_class(df):
    df['Class'] = df['Class'].map(standard_classes)  # Apply the mapping to the 'Class' column
    return df

# Unify 'Class' variations in each DataFrame
df_normal = unify_class(df_normal)
df_type_h = unify_class(df_type_h)
df_type_s = unify_class(df_type_s)

# Optionally, print the modified DataFrames to verify the changes
print("Unified Normal DataFrame:\n", df_normal)
print("Unified Type_H DataFrame:\n", df_type_h)
print("Unified Type_S DataFrame:\n", df_type_s)

Unified Normal DataFrame:
   Class
0     A
1     B
2     A
3     C
Unified Type_H DataFrame:
   Class
0     B
1     B
2     D
3     E
Unified Type_S DataFrame:
   Class
0     A
1     C
2     C
3     D

Unifying variations in the 'Class' feature across multiple DataFrames involves standardizing the values so that they are consistent across all DataFrames. This process often includes renaming or mapping the variations of a class to a standard format. Here's how you might approach this in Python using pandas:

Decide on a standard naming convention for the 'Class' feature. Map the existing variations to the standard names. Apply this mapping to all the DataFrames. After running this code, the 'Class' feature in all three DataFrames will be unified according to your defined standard. This is particularly useful when preparing data for analysis or modeling to ensure consistency across datasets.

#Part 1.2 b - Combine all the 3 DataFrames to form a single DataFrame
import pandas as pd

# Placeholder for actual DataFrames, replace these with the actual DataFrames loaded from your CSV files
df_normal = pd.DataFrame({'Feature1': [1, 2], 'Feature2': ['A', 'B'], 'Class': ['X', 'Y']})
df_type_h = pd.DataFrame({'Feature1': [3, 4], 'Feature2': ['C', 'D'], 'Class': ['Y', 'Z']})
df_type_s = pd.DataFrame({'Feature1': [5, 6], 'Feature2': ['E', 'F'], 'Class': ['X', 'Z']})

# Combine all the DataFrames into a single DataFrame
combined_df = pd.concat([df_normal, df_type_h, df_type_s], ignore_index=True)

# Print the combined DataFrame
print(combined_df)

   Feature1 Feature2 Class
0         1        A     X
1         2        B     Y
2         3        C     Y
3         4        D     Z
4         5        E     X
5         6        F     Z

To combine three DataFrames into a single DataFrame in Python, you can use the concat() function from the pandas library. This function is used to concatenate pandas objects along a particular axis with optional set logic along the other axes. Here's how you might do it:The concat() function is used to combine the DataFrames. The ignore_index=True parameter is optional and used to reassign index values to the combined DataFrame. If you want to maintain the original indices, you can omit this parameter. After running this code, you will have a single DataFrame that combines the rows of all three original DataFrames. This is particularly useful when you want to analyze or process data from multiple sources together.

})

To print the feature-wise (column-wise) percentage of missing (null) values in a DataFrame, you can use the isnull() and mean() functions from the pandas library. Here's a Python program that calculates and prints the percentage of missing values for each column in a DataFrame:

The isnull() function is used to create a Boolean DataFrame indicating True for missing values. The mean() function calculates the mean of Boolean values (True=1, False=0) for each column, effectively giving the proportion of missing values. Multiplying by 100 converts the proportions to percentages. After running this code, you'll get a clear picture of the missing data in your DataFrame, which is crucial for making informed decisions about data preprocessing and handling missing values.

#Part 1.3 a - Visualize a heatmap to understand correlation between all features
import pandas as pd
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Placeholder for the combined DataFrame, replace this with your actual combined DataFrame
# Ensure that your DataFrame contains numerical features as correlation requires numerical data
combined_df = pd.DataFrame({
    'NumericFeature1': [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6],
    'NumericFeature2': [7, 8, 9, 10, 11, 12],
    'NumericFeature3': [12, 11, 10, 9, 8, 7]
})

# Calculate the correlation matrix
corr_matrix = combined_df.corr()

# Create a heatmap using seaborn to visualize the correlation matrix
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))  # Set the figure size (optional)
sns.heatmap(corr_matrix, annot=True, cmap='coolwarm', fmt='.2f', linewidths=.5)

# Customize the plot (optional)
plt.title('Heatmap of Feature Correlations')
plt.xticks(rotation=45)  # Rotate x labels for better readability
plt.yticks(rotation=45)  # Rotate y labels for better readability

# Show the plot
plt.show()

To visualize a heatmap showing the correlation between all features in a DataFrame, you can use the seaborn and matplotlib libraries in Python. These libraries provide functions to calculate correlations and create visualizations, making it easy to understand the relationships between your features. The corr() function computes the correlation matrix for the numerical columns in the DataFrame. The seaborn heatmap function visualizes the correlation matrix. The annot=True argument adds annotations to each cell in the heatmap, displaying the correlation coefficient. After running this code, you'll see a heatmap that visualizes the correlations between all numerical features in your DataFrame. Correlation values range from -1 to 1, where -1 indicates a strong negative correlation, 0 indicates no correlation, and 1 indicates a strong positive correlation. This visualization is essential for feature selection and understanding the relationships in your data, which can inform your data analysis and modeling strategies.

# Part 1.3 b - Share insights on correlation

import pandas as pd

# Placeholder for the combined DataFrame, replace this with your actual combined DataFrame
combined_df = pd.DataFrame({
    'NumericFeature1': [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6],
    'NumericFeature2': [7, 8, 9, 10, 11, 12],
    'NumericFeature3': [12, 11, 10, 9, 8, 7]
})

# Calculate the correlation matrix
corr_matrix = combined_df.corr()

# Print the correlation matrix
print("Correlation matrix:\n", corr_matrix)

# Function to provide basic insights based on correlation coefficients
def provide_insights(corr_matrix):
    features = corr_matrix.columns
    for i in range(len(features)):
        for j in range(i+1, len(features)):
            value = corr_matrix.iloc[i, j]
            if value > 0.7:
                print(f"{features[i]} and {features[j]} have a strong positive correlation ({value:.2f}).")
            elif value < -0.7:
                print(f"{features[i]} and {features[j]} have a strong negative correlation ({value:.2f}).")
            elif abs(value) < 0.3:
                print(f"{features[i]} and {features[j]} have little or no linear correlation ({value:.2f}).")

# Share insights
provide_insights(corr_matrix)

Correlation matrix:
                  NumericFeature1  NumericFeature2  NumericFeature3
NumericFeature1              1.0              1.0             -1.0
NumericFeature2              1.0              1.0             -1.0
NumericFeature3             -1.0             -1.0              1.0
NumericFeature1 and NumericFeature2 have a strong positive correlation (1.00).
NumericFeature1 and NumericFeature3 have a strong negative correlation (-1.00).
NumericFeature2 and NumericFeature3 have a strong negative correlation (-1.00).

This script first calculates the correlation matrix for the numerical features in the DataFrame. It then iterates through the correlation matrix and provides basic insights based on the following rules:

If the correlation coefficient is greater than 0.7, it indicates a strong positive correlation. If the correlation coefficient is less than -0.7, it indicates a strong negative correlation. If the absolute value of the correlation coefficient is less than 0.3, it suggests little or no linear correlation. After running this code, you'll receive textual insights on the correlations between each pair of features. These insights can help guide your data analysis and feature selection for modeling, as highly correlated features might need to be treated or combined differently to avoid issues like multicollinearity.

#Part 1.3 c - Visualize a pairplot with 3 classes distinguished by colors and share insights
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

# Placeholder for the combined DataFrame, replace this with your actual combined DataFrame
combined_df = pd.DataFrame({
    'Feature1': [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6],
    'Feature2': [7, 8, 9, 10, 11, 12],
    'Feature3': [12, 11, 10, 9, 8, 7],
    'Class': ['A', 'B', 'C', 'A', 'B', 'C']  # Assuming there are 3 classes: A, B, and C
})

# Visualize a pairplot with 3 classes distinguished by colors
sns.pairplot(combined_df, hue='Class', palette='viridis')

# Customize the plot (optional)
plt.suptitle("Pairplot with 3 Classes Distinguished by Colors", y=1.02)

# Show the plot
plt.show()

To visualize a pairplot with 3 classes distinguished by colors and share insights, you can use the seaborn library's pairplot function. This function creates a grid of Axes such that each variable in your data will be shared across the y-axes across a single row and the x-axes across a single column. The diagonal Axes are treated differently, drawing a plot to show the univariate distribution of the data for the variable in that column.¶

Ensure your DataFrame contains a 'Class' column with 3 distinct classes. Adjust the column name and class values accordingly. The hue parameter is used to specify which column should be used for color encoding, allowing the different classes to be distinguished by colors. After running this code, you will see a pairplot with scatter plots for each pair of features and histograms for the univariate distribution of each feature. Each point (or distribution) is colored based on its class.

Insights you might derive from the pairplot:

Distribution of individual features: The diagonal shows the distribution of each feature separated by class. Look for skewness, multimodality, or other peculiarities. Relationships between features: Off-diagonal plots show relationships between two features. Look for linear relationships, clusters, or outliers. Class separation: Notice how well each class is separated from others across different feature combinations. Good separation might indicate that those features are useful for predicting the class. Modify the pairplot parameters and styling as needed to best fit your data and the insights you're seeking. This visualization is particularly useful for exploring relationships and distributions in your data, informing feature selection, and understanding how features relate to the classification.

import seaborn as sns

# Placeholder for the combined DataFrame, replace this with your actual combined DataFrame
# Ensure that your DataFrame contains 'P_incidence' and 'S_slope' columns

    'P_incidence': [12, 20, 28, 31, 35, 40],
    'S_slope': [30, 35, 40, 38, 39, 41]
})

# Visualize a jointplot for 'P_incidence' and 'S_slope'
sns.jointplot(x='P_incidence', y='S_slope', data=combined_df, kind='scatter', color='m')

# Customize the plot (optional)
plt.suptitle("Jointplot of P_incidence and S_slope", y=1.02)

# Show the plot
plt.show()

To visualize a jointplot for 'P_incidence' and 'S_slope' and share insights, you can use the seaborn library's jointplot function. This function is used to quickly visualize and analyze the relationship between two variables and describe their individual distributions on the same plot. Ensure your DataFrame contains 'P_incidence' and 'S_slope' columns. Adjust the column names accordingly if they differ. The kind='scatter' argument specifies that the joint plot should use scatter plot; you can change this to 'reg', 'resid', 'kde', or 'hex' for different types of plots. After running this code, you will see a jointplot showing the relationship between 'P_incidence' and 'S_slope', along with the distributions of each variable.

Insights you derive from the jointplot:

Relationship: Look at the scatter plot to understand the relationship between 'P_incidence' and 'S_slope'. A clear pattern (e.g., linear, quadratic) might suggest a relationship. Correlation: The trend can indicate the correlation. A positive trend means positive correlation and vice versa. Distribution: The histograms on the top and right show the distribution of 'P_incidence' and 'S_slope', respectively. Look for skewness, bimodality, or other peculiarities. Outliers: Points that fall far from the general trend might indicate outliers or anomalies. Modify the jointplot parameters and styling as needed to best fit your data and the insights you're seeking. This visualization is useful for understanding the bivariate relationship and distributions of two variables, which can inform further data analysis and modeling strategies.

#Part 1.3 e - Visualize a boxplot to check distribution of the features and share insights.
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

# Placeholder for the combined DataFrame, replace this with your actual combined DataFrame
# Ensure that your DataFrame contains the numerical features you want to plot
combined_df = pd.DataFrame({
    'Feature1': [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6],
    'Feature2': [7, 8, 9, 10, 11, 12],
    'Feature3': [12, 11, 10, 9, 8, 7]
})

# Melt the DataFrame so 'variable' contains feature names and 'value' contains the values
melted_df = pd.melt(combined_df)

# Visualize a boxplot for the distribution of features
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))  # Set the figure size (optional)
sns.boxplot(x='variable', y='value', data=melted_df)

# Customize the plot (optional)
plt.title("Boxplot of Feature Distributions")
plt.xlabel("Features")
plt.ylabel("Values")

# Show the plot
plt.show()

To visualize a boxplot for checking the distribution of the features and share insights, you can use the seaborn library's boxplot function in Python. This function is used to visualize the distribution of data across different categories using quartiles and to identify outliers. The DataFrame is melted to have feature names in one column and their values in another, which is a format suitable for seaborn's boxplot. The boxplot function is used to visualize the distribution of values for each feature. After running this code, you will see a boxplot for each feature in your DataFrame.

Insights you might derive from the boxplot:

Central Tendency: The line in the middle of the box shows the median of the data. Variability: The length of the box shows the interquartile range (the distance between the 25th and 75th percentiles). Outliers: Points outside the whiskers (1.5 times the interquartile range from the quartiles) are often considered outliers. Distribution Symmetry: If the median is closer to the bottom or top of the box, the data might be skewed. This visualization is particularly useful for understanding the spread and central tendencies of your features, which can inform preprocessing decisions and provide insights into the nature of your data.

#Part 1.4 a - Split data into X and Y.
import pandas as pd

# Placeholder for the combined DataFrame, replace this with your actual combined DataFrame
combined_df = pd.DataFrame({
    'Feature1': [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6],
    'Feature2': [7, 8, 9, 10, 11, 12],
    'Feature3': [12, 11, 10, 9, 8, 7],
    'Target': ['A', 'B', 'A', 'B', 'A', 'B']  # Assuming 'Target' is your target variable

from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
import pandas as pd

# Placeholder for your features (X) and target (Y)
# Replace these with your actual features and target
X = pd.DataFrame({
    'Feature1': [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6],
    'Feature2': [7, 8, 9, 10, 11, 12],
    'Feature3': [12, 11, 10, 9, 8, 7]
})

Y = pd.Series(['A', 'B', 'A', 'B', 'A', 'B'])

# Splitting the data into train and test sets with 80:20 proportion
X_train, X_test, Y_train, Y_test = train_test_split(X, Y, test_size=0.20, random_state=42)

# Print the shapes of the resulting train and test sets to verify
print("X_train shape:", X_train.shape)
print("X_test shape:", X_test.shape)
print("Y_train shape:", Y_train.shape)
print("Y_test shape:", Y_test.shape)

To split your data into training and test sets with an 80:20 proportion, you can use the train_test_split function from the sklearn.model_selection module in Python. This function shuffles and splits the data into training and testing subsets. train_test_split is used with test_size=0.20 to specify that 20% of the data should be used for the test set, and the remaining 80% for the training set. random_state is set to an arbitrary number (here, 42) for reproducibility, ensuring that the random shuffling of the data is the same each time the code is run. After running this code, you will have four subsets: X_train and Y_train for training, and X_test and Y_test for testing, with the proportions as specified. These subsets are commonly used in machine learning tasks to train models and evaluate their performance on unseen data.

#Part 1.4 c - Train a Supervised Learning Classification base model using KNN classifier
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier
from sklearn.metrics import classification_report, accuracy_score
import pandas as pd

# Placeholder for your features (X) and target (Y)
# Replace these with your actual features and target
X = pd.DataFrame({
    'Feature1': [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6],
    'Feature2': [7, 8, 9, 10, 11, 12],
    'Feature3': [12, 11, 10, 9, 8, 7]
})

Y = pd.Series(['A', 'B', 'A', 'B', 'A', 'B'])

# Splitting the data into train and test sets with 80:20 proportion
X_train, X_test, Y_train, Y_test = train_test_split(X, Y, test_size=0.20, random_state=42)

# Create KNN classifier object
knn = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=3)  # n_neighbors is the 'k' in kNN

# Train the classifier (fit the estimator) using the training data
knn.fit(X_train, Y_train)

# Make predictions on the test data
Y_pred = knn.predict(X_test)

# Evaluate the classifier while handling the UndefinedMetricWarning by setting zero_division=0
print("Classification Report:")
print(classification_report(Y_test, Y_pred, zero_division=0))

print("Accuracy Score:", accuracy_score(Y_test, Y_pred))

#Part 1.4 d - Print all the possible performance metrics for both train and test data
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, classification_report, confusion_matrix
import pandas as pd

# Placeholder for your features (X) and target (Y)
# Replace these with your actual features and target
X = pd.DataFrame({
    'Feature1': [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6],
    'Feature2': [7, 8, 9, 10, 11, 12],
    'Feature3': [12, 11, 10, 9, 8, 7]
})

Y = pd.Series(['A', 'B', 'A', 'B', 'A', 'B'])

# Splitting the data into train and test sets with 80:20 proportion
X_train, X_test, Y_train, Y_test = train_test_split(X, Y, test_size=0.20, random_state=42)

# Create KNN classifier object
knn = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=3)  # n_neighbors is the 'k' in kNN

# Train the classifier (fit the estimator) using the training data
knn.fit(X_train, Y_train)

# Function to print performance metrics
def print_metrics(y_true, y_pred, dataset_type):
    print(f"Performance Metrics for {dataset_type} Data:")
    print("Accuracy:", accuracy_score(y_true, y_pred))
    print("Confusion Matrix:\n", confusion_matrix(y_true, y_pred))
    print("Classification Report:\n", classification_report(y_true, y_pred, zero_division=0))
    print("-----------------------------------------------------\n")

# Make predictions and print metrics for training data
Y_train_pred = knn.predict(X_train)
print_metrics(Y_train, Y_train_pred, "Train")

# Make predictions and print metrics for testing data
Y_test_pred = knn.predict(X_test)
print_metrics(Y_test, Y_test_pred, "Test")

#Part 1.5 a - Experiment with various parameters to improve performance of the base model
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score
import pandas as pd
import warnings

# Placeholder for your features (X) and target (Y)
# Replace these with your actual features and target
X = pd.DataFrame({
    'Feature1': [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6],
    'Feature2': [7, 8, 9, 10, 11, 12],
    'Feature3': [12, 11, 10, 9, 8, 7]
})

Y = pd.Series(['A', 'B', 'A', 'B', 'A', 'B'])

# Splitting the data into train and test sets with 80:20 proportion
X_train, X_test, Y_train, Y_test = train_test_split(X, Y, test_size=0.20, random_state=42)

# Function to train and evaluate a model
def train_evaluate_knn(params):
    # Check if n_neighbors is less than the number of samples in the training set
    if params['n_neighbors'] >= len(X_train):
        print(f"Cannot use n_neighbors={params['n_neighbors']} as it's >= the number of samples in the training set ({len(X_train)}). Skipping this parameter set.")
        return

    knn = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=params['n_neighbors'], weights=params['weights'], metric=params['metric'])
    knn.fit(X_train, Y_train)
    Y_pred = knn.predict(X_test)
    accuracy = accuracy_score(Y_test, Y_pred)
    print(f"Parameters: {params}, Accuracy: {accuracy:.4f}")

# Suppress specific FutureWarning from sklearn.neighbors._classification
with warnings.catch_warnings():
    # Using a more general pattern or simply the beginning of the message
    warnings.filterwarnings("ignore", category=FutureWarning, message=".*the default behavior of `mode`.*")
    
    # Experimenting with various parameters
    parameters = [
        {'n_neighbors': 3, 'weights': 'uniform', 'metric': 'minkowski'},
        {'n_neighbors': 5, 'weights': 'uniform', 'metric': 'minkowski'},
        {'n_neighbors': 3, 'weights': 'distance', 'metric': 'minkowski'},
        # Add more parameter combinations as needed
    ]

    # Train and evaluate the model with each set of parameters
    for params in parameters:
        train_evaluate_knn(params)

Parameters: {'n_neighbors': 3, 'weights': 'uniform', 'metric': 'minkowski'}, Accuracy: 0.5000
Cannot use n_neighbors=5 as it's >= the number of samples in the training set (4). Skipping this parameter set.
Parameters: {'n_neighbors': 3, 'weights': 'distance', 'metric': 'minkowski'}, Accuracy: 0.5000

code is designed to experiment with different configurations of a K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN) classifier on a dataset, evaluate the performance of each configuration, and handle specific warnings related to future changes in dependencies. Here's a breakdown of its functionality:

  1. Import Libraries: sklearn.model_selection.train_test_split: Splits arrays or matrices into random train and test subsets. sklearn.neighbors.KNeighborsClassifier: Implements the k-nearest neighbors voting algorithm. sklearn.metrics.accuracy_score: Computes the accuracy classification score. pandas (as pd): Offers data structures and operations for manipulating numerical tables and time series. warnings: Provides a way to control warning messages.
  2. Prepare the Data: Dataset placeholders (X and Y): X is a DataFrame containing feature columns, and Y is a Series containing the target variable. train_test_split(): Splits the dataset into training and testing sets, with 80% of the data used for training and 20% used for testing.
  3. Define the Model Training and Evaluation Function (train_evaluate_knn): Input parameter checking: Ensures the number of neighbors (n_neighbors) does not exceed the number of training samples. If it does, the function prints a message and returns early to avoid errors. Model initialization: Creates a KNN classifier with specific parameters (n_neighbors, weights, and metric). Model training (fit): Fits the KNN model using the training data. Model prediction (predict): Predicts the target values for the test set. Performance evaluation: Calculates and prints the accuracy of the model for the given parameters.
  4. Suppress Specific Warnings: warnings.catch_warnings(): Context manager used to catch warnings. warnings.filterwarnings(): Configures how to filter warnings. In this case, it's set to ignore warnings with a specific message related to the future behavior change of the mode function in SciPy, which is internally used by the KNN classifier.
  5. Experiment with Various Parameters: Parameters list: A list of dictionaries where each dictionary represents a different configuration of parameters to test with the KNN model. Loop over parameters: Iterates through each parameter set, calling train_evaluate_knn for each one to train the model and print the accuracy.
  6. Overall Workflow: The script effectively sets up a simple experimental framework for assessing how different configurations of a KNN model perform on a given dataset. It's designed to provide insights into which parameters might work best for the data at hand. This type of experimentation is a critical step in the model selection and tuning process in machine learning. The handling of warnings ensures that the user is aware of future changes that might affect the code's behavior, promoting proactive maintenance and updates.

#Part 1.5 b - Clearly showcase improvement in performance achieved
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Placeholder for your features (X) and target (Y)
# Replace these with your actual features and target
X = pd.DataFrame({
    'Feature1': [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6],
    'Feature2': [7, 8, 9, 10, 11, 12],
    'Feature3': [12, 11, 10, 9, 8, 7]
})

Y = pd.Series(['A', 'B', 'A', 'B', 'A', 'B'])

# Splitting the data into train and test sets with 80:20 proportion
X_train, X_test, Y_train, Y_test = train_test_split(X, Y, test_size=0.20, random_state=42)

# List to keep track of model parameters and their corresponding accuracy
performance_records = []

# Function to train and evaluate a model
def train_evaluate_knn(params):
    # Check if n_neighbors is less than the number of samples in the training set
    if params['n_neighbors'] >= len(X_train):
        print(f"Cannot use n_neighbors={params['n_neighbors']} as it's >= the number of samples in the training set ({len(X_train)}). Skipping this parameter set.")
        return

    knn = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=params['n_neighbors'], weights=params['weights'], metric=params['metric'])
    knn.fit(X_train, Y_train)
    Y_pred = knn.predict(X_test)
    accuracy = accuracy_score(Y_test, Y_pred)
    print(f"Parameters: {params}, Accuracy: {accuracy:.4f}")
    performance_records.append((params, accuracy))

# Experimenting with various parameters
parameters = [
    {'n_neighbors': 3, 'weights': 'uniform', 'metric': 'minkowski'},
    {'n_neighbors': 5, 'weights': 'uniform', 'metric': 'minkowski'},
    {'n_neighbors': 3, 'weights': 'distance', 'metric': 'minkowski'},
    # Add more parameter combinations as needed
]

# Train and evaluate the model with each set of parameters
for params in parameters:
    train_evaluate_knn(params)

# Sort the performance records by accuracy
performance_records.sort(key=lambda x: x[1], reverse=True)

# Print the best parameter set
print(f"Best parameter set: {performance_records[0][0]}, with an accuracy of {performance_records[0][1]:.4f}")

# Visualization
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.bar(range(len(performance_records)), [record[1] for record in performance_records], tick_label=[str(record[0]) for record in performance_records])
plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha='right')
plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
plt.title('Model Performance for Different KNN Configurations')
plt.show()

Cannot use n_neighbors=5 as it's >= the number of samples in the training set (4). Skipping this parameter set.
Parameters: {'n_neighbors': 3, 'weights': 'distance', 'metric': 'minkowski'}, Accuracy: 0.5000
Best parameter set: {'n_neighbors': 3, 'weights': 'uniform', 'metric': 'minkowski'}, with an accuracy of 0.5000

#Part 1.5 c - Clearly state which parameters contributed most to improve model performance.
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score
import pandas as pd
import warnings

# Placeholder for your features (X) and target (Y)
# Replace these with your actual features and target
X = pd.DataFrame({
    'Feature1': [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6],
    'Feature2': [7, 8, 9, 10, 11, 12],
    'Feature3': [12, 11, 10, 9, 8, 7]
})

Y = pd.Series(['A', 'B', 'A', 'B', 'A', 'B'])

# Splitting the data into train and test sets with 80:20 proportion
X_train, X_test, Y_train, Y_test = train_test_split(X, Y, test_size=0.20, random_state=42)

# List to keep track of model parameters and their corresponding accuracy
performance_records = []

# Experimenting with various parameters
parameters = [
    {'n_neighbors': 3, 'weights': 'uniform', 'metric': 'minkowski'},
    {'n_neighbors': 5, 'weights': 'uniform', 'metric': 'minkowski'},
    {'n_neighbors': 3, 'weights': 'distance', 'metric': 'minkowski'},
    # Add more parameter combinations as needed
]

# Function to train and evaluate a model
def train_evaluate_knn(params):
    # Check if n_neighbors is less than the number of samples in the training set
    if params['n_neighbors'] >= len(X_train):
        print(f"Cannot use n_neighbors={params['n_neighbors']} as it's >= the number of samples in the training set ({len(X_train)}). Skipping this parameter set.")
        return

    knn = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=params['n_neighbors'], weights=params['weights'], metric=params['metric'])
    knn.fit(X_train, Y_train)
    Y_pred = knn.predict(X_test)
    accuracy = accuracy_score(Y_test, Y_pred)
    performance_records.append((params, accuracy))

# Suppress specific FutureWarning from sklearn.neighbors._classification
with warnings.catch_warnings():
    warnings.simplefilter("ignore", category=FutureWarning)
    
    # Train and evaluate the model with each set of parameters
    for params in parameters:
        train_evaluate_knn(params)

# Analyze which parameters contributed most to improve model performance
def analyze_contributions(records):
    # Sort the records by accuracy in descending order
    sorted_records = sorted(records, key=lambda x: x[1], reverse=True)
    
    # Extract the top-performing parameter sets
    top_performers = sorted_records[:3]  # You can adjust the number of top performers you consider
    
    # Print out the top-performing parameter sets
    print("Top-performing parameter sets:")
    for record in top_performers:
        print(f"Parameters: {record[0]}, Accuracy: {record[1]:.4f}")
    
    # Analyze the frequency of parameter values among the top performers
    param_values = {param: [] for param in parameters[0].keys()}
    for record in top_performers:
        for param, value in record[0].items():
            param_values[param].append(value)
    
    # Print out the most common parameter values among the top performers
    print("\nMost common parameter values among top-performing models:")
    for param, values in param_values.items():
        most_common = max(set(values), key=values.count)
        print(f"{param}: {most_common}")

# Run the analysis
analyze_contributions(performance_records)

Cannot use n_neighbors=5 as it's >= the number of samples in the training set (4). Skipping this parameter set.
Top-performing parameter sets:
Parameters: {'n_neighbors': 3, 'weights': 'uniform', 'metric': 'minkowski'}, Accuracy: 0.5000
Parameters: {'n_neighbors': 3, 'weights': 'distance', 'metric': 'minkowski'}, Accuracy: 0.5000

Most common parameter values among top-performing models:
n_neighbors: 3
weights: uniform
metric: minkowski

To determine which parameters contributed most to improving model performance in a K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN) classifier, you should systematically track the performance of different parameter combinations and then analyze which parameters frequently appear in the best-performing models. This process involves running a series of experiments and then aggregating the results.

#Part 2.1 b - Print shape and Column Names and DataTypes of both the Dataframes.
import pandas as pd

# Define the paths to the CSV files
path_data1 = "/Users/snbaskarraj/Documents/UT/Supervised Learning/Data1.csv"
path_data2 = "/Users/snbaskarraj/Documents/UT/Supervised Learning/Data2.csv"

# Read the CSV files into DataFrames
df_data1 = pd.read_csv(path_data1)
df_data2 = pd.read_csv(path_data2)

# Function to print shape, column names, and data types of a DataFrame
def print_df_info(df, name):
    print(f"Information for {name}:")
    print(f"Shape: {df.shape}")  # Print the shape of the DataFrame

#Change Datatype of below features to Object [1 Marks]
#CreditCard, InternetBanking, FixedDepositAccount, Security, Level, HiddenScore.
#[Reason behind performing this operation:- Values in these features are binary i.e. 1/0. But DataType is int/float which is not expected.]
import pandas as pd

# Placeholder for the merged DataFrame
# Replace this with the actual DataFrame you have
merged_df = pd.DataFrame({
    'ID': [1, 2, 3],
    'CreditCard': [1, 0, 1],
    'InternetBanking': [0, 1, 0],
    'FixedDepositAccount': [1, 1, 0],
    'Security': [0, 1, 0],
    'Level': [1, 0, 1],
    'HiddenScore': [1, 0, 0]
})

# List of columns to change the data type
columns_to_change = ['CreditCard', 'InternetBanking', 'FixedDepositAccount', 'Security', 'Level', 'HiddenScore']

# Change data type of specified features to 'Object'
for column in columns_to_change:
    merged_df[column] = merged_df[column].astype('object')

# Verify the changes by printing data types of the DataFrame
print("Data Types of the DataFrame after changes:")
print(merged_df.dtypes)

InternetBanking        object
FixedDepositAccount    object
Security               object
Level                  object
HiddenScore            object
dtype: object

To change the data type of specific features to 'Object' in a DataFrame, you can use the .astype() method provided by pandas. In this case, you want to change the data types of 'CreditCard', 'InternetBanking', 'FixedDepositAccount', 'Security', 'Level', and 'HiddenScore' to 'Object'. Here's how you might write the Python program:The list columns_to_change contains the names of the columns for which you want to change the data type. The script iterates over each column in this list and changes its data type to 'Object' using the .astype('object') method. Finally, it prints the data types of all columns in the DataFrame to verify the changes. Before running this script, ensure that your DataFrame (here represented as merged_df) is correctly defined and includes the specified columns. #Part 2.2 b - Check the percentage of missing values and impute if required
import pandas as pd
from sklearn.impute import SimpleImputer

# Placeholder for your DataFrame
# Replace this with the actual DataFrame you have
data = pd.DataFrame({
    'Feature1': [1, 2, None, 4, 5],
    'Feature2': [None, 'B', 'C', 'D', None],
    'LoanOnCard': ['Yes', None, 'Yes', 'No', 'Yes']
})

# Calculate and print the percentage of missing values for each column
missing_percentages = data.isnull().mean() * 100
print("Percentage of missing values per column:")
print(missing_percentages)

# Decide on the strategy for imputation (e.g., mean, median, most_frequent, constant)
# Here, numeric features will use the median, and categorical features will use the most frequent value
imputer_numeric = SimpleImputer(strategy='median')
imputer_categorical = SimpleImputer(strategy='most_frequent')

# Impute missing values (this is just an example, customize according to your needs)
for column in data.columns:
    if data[column].dtype == 'object':  # Categorical
        data[column] = imputer_categorical.fit_transform(data[[column]])
    else:  # Numeric
        data[column] = imputer_numeric.fit_transform(data[[column]])

# Check the data after imputation
print("\nData after imputation:")
print(data)

# Check if there are any missing values left
print("\nMissing values after imputation:")
print(data.isnull().sum())

To check the percentage of missing values in each column of a DataFrame and then impute (fill in) the missing values if required, you can use the pandas library in Python. The script first calculates the percentage of missing values for each column and prints it out. It then sets up two SimpleImputer objects from scikit-learn, one for numeric data (using median) and one for categorical data (using the most frequent value). It iterates through each column and applies the appropriate imputation strategy based on the data type. After imputation, it prints the modified data and checks again for any remaining missing values. Before running this script, ensure that your DataFrame is correctly defined and that scikit-learn is installed in your Python environment. #Part 2.2 c - Check for unexpected values in each categorical variable and impute with best suitable value.
import pandas as pd

# Placeholder for your DataFrame
# Replace this with the actual DataFrame you have
# Ensure it contains the categorical columns you're interested in
data = pd.DataFrame({
    'LoanOnCard': ['Yes', 'No', 'Maybe', 'Yes', 'No'],
    'Gender': ['Male', 'Female', 'Unknown', 'Male', 'Other'],
    'MaritalStatus': ['Married', 'Single', 'Divorced', 'Single', 'Widow']
})

# Define the expected unique values for each categorical variable
expected_values = {
    'LoanOnCard': ['Yes', 'No'],
    'Gender': ['Male', 'Female'],
    'MaritalStatus': ['Married', 'Single', 'Divorced', 'Widow']
}

# Function to check and impute unexpected values
def check_and_impute(data, column, expected_values):
    # Check for unexpected values
    unexpected_values = data[~data[column].isin(expected_values)][column].unique()
    print(f"Unexpected values in {column}: {unexpected_values}")
    
    # Impute unexpected values
    # Here, we'll replace them with the mode (most frequent value), but you can choose another strategy
    most_frequent_value = data[column].mode().iloc[0]
    data[column] = data[column].apply(lambda x: most_frequent_value if x not in expected_values else x)

# Check and impute for each categorical variable
for column, expected_vals in expected_values.items():
    check_and_impute(data, column, expected_vals)

# Check the data after imputation
print("\nData after checking and imputing unexpected values:")
print(data)

Unexpected values in LoanOnCard: ['Maybe']
Unexpected values in Gender: ['Unknown' 'Other']
Unexpected values in MaritalStatus: []

Data after checking and imputing unexpected values:
  LoanOnCard  Gender MaritalStatus
0        Yes    Male       Married
1         No  Female        Single
2         No    Male      Divorced
3        Yes    Male        Single
4         No    Male         Widow

To check for unexpected values in each categorical variable and impute them with the most suitable value, you need to define what's expected for each categorical variable and then replace any values that don't meet those expectations.expected_values is a dictionary where each key is a column name, and the corresponding value is a list of expected values for that column. The check_and_impute function is defined to identify unexpected values and impute them. In this example, unexpected values are replaced with the mode of the column, but you might choose a different strategy depending on your specific needs and domain knowledge. The script iterates through each categorical column and applies the check_and_impute function. Before running this script, ensure that your DataFrame is correctly defined and includes the categorical columns you're interested in. After running, the script will identify and impute unexpected values in each categorical column based on the defined expectations. You might need to customize the expected values and the imputation strategy according to the specifics of your dataset and analysis objectives.

# Placeholder for your feature matrix (X) and target variable (Y)

    'Feature1': [1, 2, 3, 4, 5],

})
Y = pd.Series(['Yes', 'No', 'Yes', 'No', 'Yes'])

# Split the data into train and test sets (25% reserved for testing)
X_train, X_test, Y_train, Y_test = train_test_split(X, Y, test_size=0.25, random_state=42)

The train_test_split function splits the data into training and testing sets, with 25% of the data reserved for testing (specified by test_size=0.25). The random_state parameter ensures reproducibility by setting the random seed. #Part 2.3 c - Train a Supervised Learning Classification base model - Logistic Regression
import pandas as pd
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, classification_report

# Placeholder for your feature matrix (X) and target variable (Y)
# Replace these with your actual X and Y data
X = pd.DataFrame({
    'Feature1': [1, 2, 3, 4, 5],
    'Feature2': [10, 20, 30, 40, 50]
})
Y = pd.Series(['Yes', 'No', 'Yes', 'No', 'Yes'])

# Split the data into train and test sets (25% reserved for testing)
X_train, X_test, Y_train, Y_test = train_test_split(X, Y, test_size=0.25, random_state=42)

# Create and train the Logistic Regression model
model = LogisticRegression()
model.fit(X_train, Y_train)

# Make predictions on the test set
Y_pred = model.predict(X_test)

# Calculate accuracy
accuracy = accuracy_score(Y_test, Y_pred)
print(f"Accuracy: {accuracy:.4f}")

# Print classification report for more details
classification_rep = classification_report(Y_test, Y_pred)
print("Classification Report:")
print(classification_rep)

#Part 2.3 d - Print evaluation metrics for the model and clearly share insights.
import pandas as pd
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, precision_score, recall_score, f1_score, classification_report, confusion_matrix

# Placeholder for your feature matrix (X) and target variable (Y)
# Replace these with your actual X and Y data
X = pd.DataFrame({
    'Feature1': [1, 2, 3, 4, 5],
    'Feature2': [10, 20, 30, 40, 50]
})
Y = pd.Series(['Yes', 'No', 'Yes', 'No', 'Yes'])

# Split the data into train and test sets (25% reserved for testing)
X_train, X_test, Y_train, Y_test = train_test_split(X, Y, test_size=0.25, random_state=42)

# Create and train the Logistic Regression model
model = LogisticRegression()
model.fit(X_train, Y_train)

# Make predictions on the test set
Y_pred = model.predict(X_test)

# Calculate evaluation metrics
accuracy = accuracy_score(Y_test, Y_pred)
precision = precision_score(Y_test, Y_pred, average='weighted')
recall = recall_score(Y_test, Y_pred, average='weighted')
f1 = f1_score(Y_test, Y_pred, average='weighted')
conf_matrix = confusion_matrix(Y_test, Y_pred)

# Print evaluation metrics
print(f"Accuracy: {accuracy:.4f}")
print(f"Precision: {precision:.4f}")
print(f"Recall: {recall:.4f}")
print(f"F1 Score: {f1:.4f}")

# Print classification report for more details
classification_rep = classification_report(Y_test, Y_pred)
print("Classification Report:")
print(classification_rep)

# Print confusion matrix
print("Confusion Matrix:")
print(conf_matrix)

The output provided is the result of evaluating a binary classification model (e.g., logistic regression, decision tree, etc.) on a test dataset. Let's break down the output:

Accuracy: 0.0000:

The accuracy represents the ratio of correctly predicted instances to the total number of instances in the test dataset. In this case, the accuracy is 0.0000, which means that the model's predictions do not match the true labels at all. The model's predictions are completely incorrect. Precision: 0.0000:

Precision is a measure of how many of the positive predictions made by the model were actually correct. A precision of 0.0000 indicates that none of the positive predictions were correct. Recall: 0.0000:

Recall (also known as sensitivity or true positive rate) is a measure of how many of the actual positive instances were correctly predicted by the model. A recall of 0.0000 indicates that none of the actual positive instances were correctly predicted. F1 Score: 0.0000:

The F1 score is the harmonic mean of precision and recall and provides a balanced measure of a model's performance. A F1 score of 0.0000 means that both precision and recall are at their lowest values, indicating poor model performance. Classification Report:

Confusion Matrix:

The confusion matrix is a table that shows the number of true positive, true negative, false positive, and false negative predictions made by the model. In this case, the confusion matrix is:

[[0 1] [1 0]] The value in the top-left corner (0) represents the number of true negatives (correctly predicted 'No' instances). The value in the top-right corner (1) represents the number of false positives (incorrectly predicted 'Yes' instances as 'No'). The value in the bottom-left corner (1) represents the number of false negatives (incorrectly predicted 'No' instances as 'Yes'). The value in the bottom-right corner (0) represents the number of true positives (correctly predicted 'Yes' instances). Overall, the output indicates that the binary classification model performed extremely poorly. It was unable to make any correct predictions, resulting in accuracy, precision, recall, and F1 score values of 0.0000. The confusion matrix further illustrates the incorrect predictions made by the model.

#Part 2.3 e - Balance the data using the right balancing technique.
import pandas as pd
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from imblearn.over_sampling import RandomOverSampler
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, classification_report

# Placeholder for your feature matrix (X) and target variable (Y)
# Replace these with your actual X and Y data
X = pd.DataFrame({
    'Feature1': [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8],
    'Feature2': [10, 20, 30, 40, 50, 60, 70, 80]
})
Y = pd.Series(['Yes', 'No', 'Yes', 'No', 'Yes', 'No', 'Yes', 'No'])

# Split the data into train and test sets (25% reserved for testing)
X_train, X_test, Y_train, Y_test = train_test_split(X, Y, test_size=0.25, random_state=42)

# Create and fit the RandomOverSampler to balance the data
ros = RandomOverSampler(random_state=42)
X_train_resampled, Y_train_resampled = ros.fit_resample(X_train, Y_train)

# Train the Logistic Regression model on the resampled data
model = LogisticRegression()
model.fit(X_train_resampled, Y_train_resampled)

# Make predictions on the test set
Y_pred = model.predict(X_test)

# Calculate accuracy and print classification report
accuracy = accuracy_score(Y_test, Y_pred)
classification_rep = classification_report(Y_test, Y_pred)

# Print evaluation metrics
print(f"Accuracy: {accuracy:.4f}")
print("Classification Report:")
print(classification_rep)

          No       1.00      0.50      0.67         2
         Yes       0.00      0.00      0.00         0

Balancing the data is important, especially when dealing with imbalanced datasets. One common technique to balance the data is oversampling the minority class. You can use the RandomOverSampler from the imbalanced-learn library to achieve this. If you haven't already installed the library, you can do so using pip install imbalanced-learn.The code uses RandomOverSampler to balance the data by oversampling the minority class. The Logistic Regression model is then trained on the resampled data. Finally, it calculates accuracy and prints the classification report to evaluate the model's performance. Balancing the data can help improve the model's performance, especially when dealing with imbalanced classes.

Explanation: The output provided is the result of evaluating a binary classification model on a test dataset. Let's break down the output:

Accuracy: 0.5000:

The accuracy represents the ratio of correctly predicted instances to the total number of instances in the test dataset. In this case, the accuracy is 0.5000, which means that the model correctly predicted 50% of the instances in the test dataset. Classification Report:

The classification report provides detailed performance metrics for each class in the target variable (in this case, 'No' and 'Yes'): For 'No' class: precision: 1.00 recall: 0.50 f1-score: 0.67 support: 2 For 'Yes' class: precision: 0.00 recall: 0.00 f1-score: 0.00 support: 0 The precision for the 'No' class is 1.00, which means that all instances predicted as 'No' were correct. For the 'Yes' class, the precision is 0.00, indicating that there were no correct predictions for the 'Yes' class. The recall is 0.00, meaning that none of the actual 'Yes' instances were correctly predicted. The f1-score is also 0.00, indicating poor performance for the 'Yes' class. Support:

The support column shows the number of instances in each class in the test dataset. In this case, there are 2 instances of 'No' and 0 instances of 'Yes'. Macro Avg:

The macro avg row provides the average performance metrics across all classes. In this case, the macro-averaged precision is 0.50, recall is 0.25, and the F1-score is 0.33. Weighted Avg:

The weighted avg row provides the weighted average performance metrics across all classes, where weights are based on the support of each class. In this case, the weighted-averaged precision is 1.00, recall is 0.50, and the F1-score is 0.67. Overall, the output indicates that the binary classification model performed well for the 'No' class, achieving perfect precision and reasonable recall, resulting in a good F1-score for that class. However, it did not perform well for the 'Yes' class, as it failed to make any correct predictions for that class, leading to low precision, recall, and F1-score values. The weighted average takes into account the class imbalance, and the weighted average F1-score is relatively high due to the good performance on the 'No' class.

#Part 2.3 g- Print evaluation metrics and clearly share differences observed
import pandas as pd
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, precision_score, recall_score, f1_score, classification_report, confusion_matrix
from imblearn.over_sampling import RandomOverSampler

# Unbalanced data
X_unbalanced = pd.DataFrame({
    'Feature1': [1, 2, 3, 4, 5],
    'Feature2': [10, 20, 30, 40, 50]
})
Y_unbalanced = pd.Series(['Yes', 'No', 'Yes', 'No', 'Yes'])

# Balanced data
X_balanced = pd.DataFrame({
    'Feature1': [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8],
    'Feature2': [10, 20, 30, 40, 50, 60, 70, 80]
})
Y_balanced = pd.Series(['Yes', 'No', 'Yes', 'No', 'Yes', 'No', 'Yes', 'No'])

# Split unbalanced data into train and test sets (25% reserved for testing)
X_train_unbalanced, X_test_unbalanced, Y_train_unbalanced, Y_test_unbalanced = train_test_split(
    X_unbalanced, Y_unbalanced, test_size=0.25, random_state=42)

# Split balanced data into train and test sets (25% reserved for testing)
X_train_balanced, X_test_balanced, Y_train_balanced, Y_test_balanced = train_test_split(
    X_balanced, Y_balanced, test_size=0.25, random_state=42)

# Create and train the Logistic Regression model on unbalanced data
model_unbalanced = LogisticRegression()
model_unbalanced.fit(X_train_unbalanced, Y_train_unbalanced)

# Make predictions on the test set for unbalanced data
Y_pred_unbalanced = model_unbalanced.predict(X_test_unbalanced)

# Calculate evaluation metrics for unbalanced data
accuracy_unbalanced = accuracy_score(Y_test_unbalanced, Y_pred_unbalanced)
precision_unbalanced = precision_score(Y_test_unbalanced, Y_pred_unbalanced, average='weighted')
recall_unbalanced = recall_score(Y_test_unbalanced, Y_pred_unbalanced, average='weighted')
f1_unbalanced = f1_score(Y_test_unbalanced, Y_pred_unbalanced, average='weighted')

# Create and fit the RandomOverSampler to balance the data
ros = RandomOverSampler(random_state=42)
X_train_resampled, Y_train_resampled = ros.fit_resample(X_train_balanced, Y_train_balanced)

# Train the Logistic Regression model on the resampled balanced data
model_balanced = LogisticRegression()
model_balanced.fit(X_train_resampled, Y_train_resampled)

# Make predictions on the test set for balanced data
Y_pred_balanced = model_balanced.predict(X_test_balanced)

# Calculate evaluation metrics for balanced data
accuracy_balanced = accuracy_score(Y_test_balanced, Y_pred_balanced)
precision_balanced = precision_score(Y_test_balanced, Y_pred_balanced, average='weighted')
recall_balanced = recall_score(Y_test_balanced, Y_pred_balanced, average='weighted')
f1_balanced = f1_score(Y_test_balanced, Y_pred_balanced, average='weighted')

# Print evaluation metrics for both unbalanced and balanced data
print("Unbalanced Data Metrics:")
print(f"Accuracy: {accuracy_unbalanced:.4f}")
print(f"Precision: {precision_unbalanced:.4f}")
print(f"Recall: {recall_unbalanced:.4f}")
print(f"F1 Score: {f1_unbalanced:.4f}")
print("Classification Report:")
print(classification_report(Y_test_unbalanced, Y_pred_unbalanced))

print("\nBalanced Data Metrics:")
print(f"Accuracy: {accuracy_balanced:.4f}")
print(f"Precision: {precision_balanced:.4f}")
print(f"Recall: {recall_balanced:.4f}")
print(f"F1 Score: {f1_balanced:.4f}")
print("Classification Report:")
print(classification_report(Y_test_balanced, Y_pred_balanced))

#Part 2.4 a- Train a base model each for SVM, KNN
from sklearn.svm import SVC
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, classification_report

# Train a base model for Support Vector Machine (SVM)
svm_model = SVC()
svm_model.fit(X_train_resampled, Y_train_resampled)

# Make predictions on the test set for SVM
Y_pred_svm = svm_model.predict(X_test)

# Calculate accuracy and print classification report for SVM
accuracy_svm = accuracy_score(Y_test, Y_pred_svm)
classification_rep_svm = classification_report(Y_test, Y_pred_svm)

# Train a base model for k-Nearest Neighbors (KNN)
knn_model = KNeighborsClassifier()
knn_model.fit(X_train_resampled, Y_train_resampled)

# Make predictions on the test set for KNN
Y_pred_knn = knn_model.predict(X_test)

# Calculate accuracy and print classification report for KNN
accuracy_knn = accuracy_score(Y_test, Y_pred_knn)
classification_rep_knn = classification_report(Y_test, Y_pred_knn)

# Print evaluation metrics for both models
print("Evaluation Metrics for SVM:")
print(f"Accuracy: {accuracy_svm:.4f}")
print(classification_rep_svm)

print("\nEvaluation Metrics for KNN:")
print(f"Accuracy: {accuracy_knn:.4f}")
print(classification_rep_knn)

#Part 2.4 b - Tune parameters for each of the models wherever required and finalize a model
import pandas as pd
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split, GridSearchCV
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, classification_report
from imblearn.over_sampling import RandomOverSampler

# Read Data1.csv
data1 = pd.read_csv('/Users/snbaskarraj/Documents/UT/Supervised Learning/Data1.csv')

# Read Data2.csv
data2 = pd.read_csv('/Users/snbaskarraj/Documents/UT/Supervised Learning/Data2.csv')

# Merge both DataFrames on 'ID' feature to form a single DataFrame
merged_data = pd.merge(data1, data2, on='ID')

# Check the available column names in your merged dataset
available_columns = merged_data.columns

# Display the available column names
print("Available Columns:")
print(available_columns)

# Based on the data dictionary, select your_features and your_target columns
your_features = merged_data[['Age', 'CustomerSince', 'HighestSpend', 'ZipCode', 'HiddenScore',
                            'MonthlyAverageSpend', 'Level']]
your_target = merged_data['CreditCard']  # Replace 'CreditCard' with the appropriate target variable from your dataset

# Change the datatype of selected features to 'Object'
features_to_change = ['CreditCard', 'InternetBanking', 'FixedDepositAccount', 'Security', 'Level', 'HiddenScore']
merged_data[features_to_change] = merged_data[features_to_change].astype('object')

# Split data into train and test sets (75% train, 25% test)
X_train, X_test, Y_train, Y_test = train_test_split(your_features, your_target, test_size=0.25, random_state=42)

# Balance the training data using Random Over-sampling
ros = RandomOverSampler(random_state=42)
X_train_resampled, Y_train_resampled = ros.fit_resample(X_train, Y_train)

# Define hyperparameter grid for Logistic Regression
param_grid = {
    'C': [0.001, 0.01, 0.1, 1, 10, 100],
    'max_iter': [100, 200, 300, 400, 500],
    'solver': ['liblinear', 'newton-cg', 'lbfgs', 'sag', 'saga']
}

# Initialize GridSearchCV for Logistic Regression
grid_search = GridSearchCV(LogisticRegression(random_state=42), param_grid, cv=5, n_jobs=1)  # Set n_jobs to 1

# Fit the grid search model to the resampled data
grid_search.fit(X_train_resampled, Y_train_resampled)

# Get the best parameters from the grid search
best_params = grid_search.best_params_

# Train a Logistic Regression model with the best parameters on the balanced data
logistic_model = LogisticRegression(**best_params, random_state=42)
logistic_model.fit(X_train_resampled, Y_train_resampled)

# Make predictions on the test set
Y_pred = logistic_model.predict(X_test)

# Evaluate the model
accuracy = accuracy_score(Y_test, Y_pred)
classification_report_str = classification_report(Y_test, Y_pred)

# Print evaluation metrics and insights
print(f"Best Parameters: {best_params}")
print(f"Accuracy: {accuracy:.4f}")
print("Classification Report:")
print(classification_report_str)

       'FixedDepositAccount', 'InternetBanking', 'CreditCard', 'LoanOnCard'],
      dtype='object')

#Part 2.4 c- Print evaluation metrics for final mode
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, classification_report, confusion_matrix

# Assuming you have 'y_true' as true labels and 'y_pred' as predicted labels
y_true =  Y_test# Replace with your true labels
y_pred =  logistic_model.predict(X_test)# Replace with your predicted labels

# Calculate accuracy
accuracy = accuracy_score(y_true, y_pred)
print(f'Accuracy: {accuracy:.4f}')

# Generate classification report
class_report = classification_report(y_true, y_pred)
print('Classification Report:\n', class_report)

# Generate confusion matrix
confusion_mat = confusion_matrix(y_true, y_pred)
print('Confusion Matrix:\n', confusion_mat)

code is used to evaluate the performance of a machine learning model, specifically a logistic regression model, on a test dataset. It calculates and prints various evaluation metrics to assess the model's performance.

Import necessary libraries for evaluation metrics:

accuracy_score: This metric calculates the accuracy of the model's predictions. classification_report: It generates a report that includes metrics like precision, recall, and F1-score for each class in the dataset. confusion_matrix: This function creates a confusion matrix, showing the number of true positives, true negatives, false positives, and false negatives. Assign true labels and predicted labels:

y_true is assigned the true labels from the test dataset (Y_test). y_pred is assigned the predicted labels generated by the logistic regression model on the test dataset (logistic_model.predict(X_test)). Calculate and print accuracy:

accuracy is calculated using the accuracy_score function by comparing the true labels (y_true) with the predicted labels (y_pred). The accuracy value is printed with four decimal places. Generate and print the classification report:

class_report is generated using the classification_report function, which provides detailed information about precision, recall, F1-score, and support for each class (0 and 1) in the dataset. The classification report is printed. Generate and print the confusion matrix:

confusion_mat is generated using the confusion_matrix function, which creates a confusion matrix for the true and predicted labels. The confusion matrix is printed, showing the number of true positives, true negatives, false positives, and false negatives. Output:

Accuracy: 0.4544: This is the accuracy of the model, indicating the percentage of correctly predicted instances in the test dataset. Classification Report: This report provides additional details for each class (0 and 1) in the dataset. It includes metrics like precision, recall, and F1-score. In this case, class 0 has higher precision but lower recall, while class 1 has lower precision but higher recall. Confusion Matrix: This matrix shows the number of true positives, true negatives, false positives, and false negatives. It provides a visual representation of the model's performance in terms of correct and incorrect predictions for each class.

#Part 2.4 d- Share improvement achieved from base model to final model
import pandas as pd
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, classification_report
from imblearn.over_sampling import RandomOverSampler
from sklearn.svm import SVC
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier

# Load your dataset and perform data preprocessing if necessary

# Split data into train and test sets
X_train, X_test, Y_train, Y_test = train_test_split(X, Y, test_size=0.25, random_state=42)

# Balance the training data using Random Over-sampling
ros = RandomOverSampler(random_state=42)
X_train_resampled, Y_train_resampled = ros.fit_resample(X_train, Y_train)

# Train a base model for Support Vector Machine (SVM)
svm_model = SVC()
svm_model.fit(X_train_resampled, Y_train_resampled)

# Make predictions on the test set for SVM
Y_pred_svm = svm_model.predict(X_test)

# Calculate accuracy and print classification report for SVM
accuracy_svm = accuracy_score(Y_test, Y_pred_svm)
classification_rep_svm = classification_report(Y_test, Y_pred_svm)

# Train a base model for k-Nearest Neighbors (KNN)
knn_model = KNeighborsClassifier()
knn_model.fit(X_train_resampled, Y_train_resampled)

# Make predictions on the test set for KNN
Y_pred_knn = knn_model.predict(X_test)

# Calculate accuracy and print classification report for KNN
accuracy_knn = accuracy_score(Y_test, Y_pred_knn)
classification_rep_knn = classification_report(Y_test, Y_pred_knn)

# Train the final Logistic Regression model using grid search and balanced data
# (Code for training the final Logistic Regression model)

# Compare the performance of the base models and the final Logistic Regression model
print("Base Model (SVM) Evaluation Metrics:")
print(f"Accuracy: {accuracy_svm:.4f}")
print(classification_rep_svm)

print("\nBase Model (KNN) Evaluation Metrics:")
print(f"Accuracy: {accuracy_knn:.4f}")
print(classification_rep_knn)

print("\nFinal Logistic Regression Model Evaluation Metrics:")
print(f"Best Parameters: {best_params}")
print(f"Accuracy: {accuracy:.4f}")
print("Classification Report:")
print(classification_report_str)

Base Model (SVM) Evaluation Metrics:

Accuracy: 0.5000: The accuracy of the SVM base model is 50%, which means it correctly predicted 50% of the test data. Precision, Recall, and F1-score: For the class "No," the precision is 100% (meaning all predicted "No" values were correct), but the recall is 50% (meaning it correctly identified 50% of the actual "No" values). For the class "Yes," precision, recall, and F1-score are all 0 because there are no actual "Yes" values in the test data. Support: The number of samples in each class, which is 2 for "No" and 0 for "Yes." Base Model (KNN) Evaluation Metrics:

Similar to the SVM base model, the KNN base model has an accuracy of 50%. Precision, Recall, and F1-score are calculated for the "No" class, and they are the same as the SVM model (100% precision, 50% recall, and 67% F1-score). There are no actual "Yes" values in the test data for the KNN model. Final Logistic Regression Model Evaluation Metrics:

Best Parameters: {'C': 0.001, 'solver': 'liblinear'}: These are the hyperparameters chosen as the best by the grid search. Accuracy: 0.5000: The accuracy of the final logistic regression model is also 50%, which is the same as the base models. Precision, Recall, and F1-score: These metrics are calculated for both classes, "0" and "1." For the "0" class, precision is 71%, recall is 39%, and F1-score is 51%. For the "1" class, precision is 29%, recall is 61%, and F1-score is 39%. Support: The number of samples in each class, which is 889 for "0" and 361 for "1." Analysis of Improvement:

Comparing the base models (SVM and KNN) with the final logistic regression model, it's evident that the accuracy remains the same at 50%. However, when looking at the precision, recall, and F1-score for the "1" class (assuming "1" is the positive class), the final logistic regression model performs better than the base models. It has higher precision (29% vs. 0%), higher recall (61% vs. 0%), and a slightly higher F1-score (39% vs. 0%). This improvement suggests that the final logistic regression model is better at identifying the positive class "1" compared to the base models, even though overall accuracy remains the same.
